snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Dr Mike, I'm wondering what your opinion is on chiropractic and maybe you could do a video on it?

Ive been dealing with unexplained pain for a few months and while waiting for my appointment to see a rheumatologist my doctor referred me to a chiropractic clinic. I saw them for 12 weeks and it made absolutely zero difference to my situation, just cost me money and occasionally made the pain much much worse. After a session that put me in particularly bad pain, I decided to google about chiropractic and discovered that it is actually a pseudoscience and there are no clinical trials that show it to be any more beneficial than placebo, chiropractors do not attend any form of medical school education and are not doctors, they only complete the normal 3 or 4 years of university study as you would for any bachelors or masters degree.

I'm wondering if this is all true and if it is true then why would my family doctor send me to them? Was it to keep me busy while I waited for the rheumatology appointment so that I believe something is happening with my medical care? It's really common for GP's to refer patients to chiropractic, yet it is no more beneficial in studies than going for a massage but much more expensive for the patients. I live in the UK so its not as if there is a financial motive for it when referring a patient to receive subsidised care.

This may get lost in the thousands of comments but im REALLY curious what your thoughts are on this and maybe other complimentary care options that are technically pseudoscience but patients get referred to anyway?

snippet.textDisplay:
There is definitely a good way to do social media as a medical professional, and those two videos were not it. It makes the field look terrible, while also discouraging to those who already delay care their due to the fear of being dismissed.

You never know what's really going on until you take a patient's concerns seriously and investigate it. Plus, I've heard stories of people who were only properly diagnosed after exaggerating their symptoms due to the fact that no one would take them seriously before doing so. So in my mind, even if an assessment suggests they are exaggerating or faking symptoms, then it's our job to figure out the source of the problem causing a discrepancy between the assessment and what they're reporting, instead of just dismissing them. What if we're missing something important in the assessment? What if this patient is just atypical? Might it be a neurological or mental health issue? If we don't investigate, then we are doing a major disservice to our patients.

Thank you, Dr. Mike for putting good information out there.

snippet.textDisplay:
As a nurse, I agree this is NOT okay. As a medical professional, you are in a position of seeing someone at their most vulnerable, which means you hold immense power and influence over the situation. I consider it an honor and a privilege to care for those who are at their sickest. It doesn't matter what I think - if a patient says they are experiencing symptoms different from their baseline, it is my JOB to help support that person and the doctor to help make that person well again.
I purposely go above and beyond for patients because I have been a patient with a horrible experience of not being believed because I didn't "fit" what the medical team thought I should present as. I once had severe Pancreatitis but the doctor believed it was only indigestion and gave me an antacid which flared my pain even more. He refused to give me any pain meds for 4 hours until the results of my bloodwork and ultrasound came back showing the problem. He did apologize to me for not believing me though, and I could tell that was hard for him.
All that to say, I am thankful I learned what patients go through sometimes, and now that I am a nurse myself, I refuse to be Nurse Ratchet to any of my patients no matter how difficult!
